      "have the function $f$ with two cases:\n- If $x$ is not irrational (i.e., $x$ is rational), then $f(x) = | \\lfloor x \\rfloor |$.\n- If $x$ is irrational, then $f(x) = \\lceil x \\rceil^2$.\n\nLet's compute each term:\n\n1. $f(8^{1/3})$: $8^{1/3} = 2$ which is rational. So $f(2) = | \\lfloor 2 \\rfloor | = |2| = 2$.\n2. $f(-\\pi)$: $-\\pi$ is irrational. So $f(-\\pi) = \\lceil -\\pi \\rceil^2$. Since $-\\pi \\approx -3.14159$, $\\lceil -\\pi \\rceil = -3$. Thus, $f(-\\pi) = (-3)^2 = 9$.\n3. $f(\\sqrt{50})$: $\\sqrt{50}$ is irrational. So $f(\\sqrt{50}) = \\lceil \\sqrt{50} \\rceil^2$. Since $7^2 = 49$ and $8^2 = 64$, $7 < \\sqrt{50} < 8$. Thus, $\\lceil \\sqrt{50} \\rceil = 8$. So $f(\\sqrt{50}) = 8^2 = 64$.\n4. $f(9/2)$: $9/2 = 4.5$ is rational. So $f(4.5) = | \\lfloor 4.5 \\rfloor | = |4| = 4$.\n\nSumming these: $2 + 9 + 64 + 4 = 79$.\n\nNow, let's prove this in Lean 4.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : (8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ) = (2 : тДЭ) := by\n  have h1 : (8 : тДЭ) = (2 : тДЭ) ^ (3 : тДЭ) := by norm_num\n  rw [h1]\n  rw [тЖР Real.rpow_mul]\n  norm_num\n  all_goals norm_num\n```\n\nNow we have $8^{1/3} = 2$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h3 : ┬м Irrational ((8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ)) := by\n  rw [h2]\n  simp\n```\n\nSince $8^{1/3} = 2$ which is rational, we use the first case of $f$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h4 : f ((8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ)) = abs (Int.floor ((8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ))) := by \n  apply hтВА ((8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ))\n  exact h3\n```\n\nNow compute $f(8^{1/3})$:\n\nSince $8^{1/3} = 2$, $\\lfloor 2 \\rfloor = 2$, $|2| = 2$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h5 : f ((8 : тДЭ) ^ (1 / 3 : тДЭ)) = (2 : тДЭ) := by\n  rw [h4]\n  rw [h2]\n  norm_num [abs_of_nonneg, Int.floor_eq_iff]\n```\n\nNow, let's compute $f(-\\pi)$.\n\nSince $-\\pi$ is irrational, we use the second case of $f$:\n\n$f(-\\pi) = \\lceil -\\pi \\rceil^2$. Now, $-\\pi \\approx -3.14159$, so $\\lceil -\\pi \\rceil = -3$. Therefore, $f(-\\pi) = (-3)^2 = 9$.\n\n```tactics\nhave h6 : Irrational (-Real.pi) := by \n  ap